  "summary": "After a woman leaves his room, Mr. Castor waits in silence before rushing out of a building. He navigates through a courtyard, passing two drivers, and heads toward a street in hopes of escaping via a special train at the station.\n\nMeanwhile, Inspector Crumb and Detective Croft interview witnesses regarding a murder at a cinema. Mr. Liddell describes a tall, bald, dark-skinned man with a limp who entered the theater after the film had started; Liddell believes the man pretended to stumble to stab a victim. The doorman, Jamison, reports seeing a man collapsed in the cheap ticket section with blood on his coat. Jamison notes that several people left the area shortly before the discovery, including Mr. Jeffrey Parnell and a young man named Sam Baker.\n\nHercule Poirot and Hastings arrive to assist the investigation. Colonel Anderson informs them that the victim is George Erskine, a barber, and that an ABC book was found near his feet. This is identified as another \"ABC murder,\" though the method was a stabbing rather than the previous methods of strangulation or blunt force trauma.\n\nThe next witness, Roger Emmanuel Downes, the headmaster of Heathfield School, recounts how he discovered the body after attempting to wake a man he thought was sleeping in the seat next to him. Colonel Anderson confronts Downes, noting that Downes has a similar height and build to the deceased and was wearing a woolen scarf. Anderson suggests the killer actually intended to stab Downes but mistakenly attacked Erskine instead. The revelation causes Downes to collapse from shock.",
